epistrophe  
a word or expression is repeated at the end of successive
phrases, clauses or lines.

euphemism  
substitution of an agreeable or at least non-offensive
expression for one whose plainer meaning might be harsh or unpleasant.

hyperbaton  
(see also inversion) (Greek for ”stepping over”): a figure of
syntactic dislocation where phrase or words that belong together are
separated.

inversion  
the usual word order is rearranged, often for the effect of
emphasis or to maintain the meter (a type of hyperbaton).

hyperbole  
obvious exaggeration for emphasis or for rhetorical effect.

irony  
a discrepancy between the expression of something and the intended
meaning; the words say one thing but mean another.

oxymoron  
(Greek for “sharp-dull”): a paradoxical utterance that conjoins
